ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, we established CNPs derived from bio-waste of peanut shells with a protective layer of β-cyclodextrins (β-CDs) as probes for bioimaging (

                     Scheme 1
                     ). The resulting nanoparticles exhibited highly stable optical absorption and emission properties under aqueous solution. Predominantly, a series of in vitro cell experiments showed that β-CD-coated CNPs not only showed the appropriate biocompatibility with such extremely low cytotoxicity under normal cells but also showed a substantially enhanced uptake by cells, leading to improved fluorescence properties and stability within the cancer cells. In silico studies clearly demonstrated that β-CD-coated CNPs interact with CDK-2 proteins, targeting them in order to inhibit the growth of cancer cells via hydrogen bonding and hydrophobic interactions. Thus, this newly discovered nanoparticle system from a bio-waste plant of peanut shell may introduce a strategy for developing highly stable fluorescent nanoprobes, enabling efficient monitoring of multiple targets during bioimaging and dynamic biological processes.
